                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-148135 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-kris-kross-music-group tag-kristofferson-kris per-kristofferson-kris org-kris-kross-music-group" id="post-148135">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Star Is Born</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Kristopher Jansma			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2013-08-22T00:30:18+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 21, 2013 8:30 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 21, 2013 8:30 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My wife gave birth to our first child this April. When you tell people that you&#x2019;re expecting, the second question they ask (after the gender) is, &#x201C;Do you have a name picked out?&#x201D; Because we make
                                        a living working with books, my wife and I take the business of naming seriously, and our friends seemed to expect us to pluck a name from literary obscurity.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But I have always had a complicated relationship with my name. When I was young, Kris Kringle was the only other Kris-with-a-K I knew, until I turned 10 and the charts were topped by Kris Kross. My classmates kept telling
                                        me to &#x201C;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=010KyIQjkTk">jump jump</a>&#x201D; and wear my clothes backwards. Then there was the summer I turned 13, when a teen fashion magazine began to send me complimentary
                                        tampons, believing Kris to be short for Kristen or Kristina. It wasn&#x2019;t until high school that I learned the truth about my name: My mother had named me after the country-music star and actor Kris Kristofferson.
                                        <span
                                            id="more-148135"></span>
                                    </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> That crusty vampire hunter from the &#x201C;Blade&#x201D; movie? &#x201C;When I was your age he was very attractive; I had a little crush on him,&#x201D; my mother explained. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As a fiction writer, I know that names can set the tone for how a character is perceived. A &#x201C;Yossarian&#x201D; cannot quite be taken seriously, whereas a &#x201C;Gatsby&#x201D; must indeed be Great. In books
                                        characters are named to fit their personalities, but in real life our parents give us names at birth that hold a fateful power that cannot be evaded, no matter how many clever nicknames are adopted. I was sure that
                                        mine was a B-movie black mark. (&#x201C;Did you see &#x2018;Planet of the Apes&#x2019;?&#x201D; I&#x2019;d ask. &#x201C;No, I mean, the remake.&#x201D;) </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The more I told the story, the more Kristofferson trivia came my way. A friend found one of his albums in the tape deck of a rental car. &#x201C;He&#x2019;s actually pretty good!&#x201D; he called to tell me, shouting
                                        over the twanging. In graduate school I mentioned the story to one of my classmates and he seemed genuinely impressed: &#x201C;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_RLiuPRMJy8">Kristofferson played with Johnny Cash</a>,
                                        man. He&#x2019;s got some serious hipster credibility.&#x201D; It turns out that, like me, Kristofferson had studied creative writing in college. He was a Rhodes scholar, a Golden Gloves boxing champion and a captain
                                        in the Army, and he dated Janis Joplin. He even wrote her iconic &#x201C;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WXV_QjenbDw">Me and Bobby McGee</a>.&#x201D; I began to wonder if I hadn&#x2019;t sold my mother
                                        short.</p>
                                    <div class="w592">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/22/opinion/0822PRIVATELIVES/0822PRIVATELIVES-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/22/opinion/0822PRIVATELIVES/0822PRIVATELIVES-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/08/22/opinion/0822PRIVATELIVES/0822PRIVATELIVES-tmagArticle.jpg"
                                                    id="100000002397403" width="592" height="392" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="392">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="592">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Simon Roussin</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I asked her about it again, she explained that she&#x2019;d first seen Kristofferson in the Barbra Streisand film &#x201C;A Star Is Born.&#x201D; The film, an updated version of two previous movies with the same
                                        name, was the &#x201C;Titanic&#x201D; of 1976, the year my parents met and graduated from high school. Three years later they married and had their first dance to &#x201C;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MIrKmLJnLqU">Evergreen</a>,&#x201D;
                                        the love song from the film. Three years after that, I was born. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These were not the kinds of details that would enhance my hipster cred. Still, I rented the movie, prepared to discover that I&#x2019;d been named after a 1970s beefcake my teenage mother had the hots for. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;A Star is Born&#x201D; begins with a violent, impatient crowd at a rock concert. Kristofferson rolls up in a Cadillac. Gary Busey helps him do a bump of coke and then pushes him onto the stage. Kristofferson
                                        fumbles through the first song and then tells the audience that they can go to hell. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Less than 10 minutes into the film, and I was scandalized. Casual drug use? Oversexed groupies? When I was growing up my mother sold computer software, wore shoulder pads and voted for Ross Perot. This was her favorite
                                        movie? </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It turns out that &#x201C;A Star Is Born&#x201D; is a totally gripping film. It takes off after Kristofferson meets Barbra Streisand in a nightclub. They write a song together and make love in a soapy bathtub. They
                                        marry and have more sex out in the wilderness. Her star rises as his falls. One morning, Kristofferson wakes up, pops open a beer, and speeds off down empty roads, switching between 8-tracks of his music and hers.
                                        Cut to the wreckage of his car on the side of the road and Babs crying over his dead body. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was actually really cool. Kristofferson&#x2019;s rock star is fragile and a little lonely; he is a man lost in search of greater truths, simultaneously invulnerable and broken, complex and captivating &#x2014; exactly
                                        the sort of character I am drawn to create in my own writing. I found I didn&#x2019;t mind being his namesake after all. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I told my mother I&#x2019;d seen the film, she was glad I had liked it, but she assured me that it hadn&#x2019;t been that big a deal to her. There had been no deep soul-searching or long hours of contemplation
                                        in the decision to name me Kris. She&#x2019;d just liked it. She remembered thinking it might stand out and make me feel special. I&#x2019;ve spent far more hours pondering it than she ever did. But this is who
                                        she raised me to be: a solver of puzzles, a seeker of larger meanings. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Once, the idea of naming my children after the spunkiest or wisest characters in literature would have been appealing. I could have tested potential dinner party guests to see if they got the reference. But now I couldn&#x2019;t
                                        imagine putting that kind of pressure on such a tiny person. How could I saddle a son with a name like &#x201C;Holden&#x201D;? Or say, &#x201C;My boy, you are named Fitzgerald after the great writer &#x2026; slash
                                        alcoholic?&#x201D; </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the end, it took my wife and me about 10 minutes to choose. We just picked something we liked. Our son&#x2019;s name is Joshua, and whatever meanings lie within it are his to invent.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.kristopherjansma.com/ ">Kristopher Jansma</a> is the author of the novel &#x201C;The Unchangeable Spots of Leopards.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 08/25/2013, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">9</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: A Star Is Born.</p>
